# PART 1: TREES — FUNDAMENTALS

---

## 1.1 What Is a Tree?

A tree is like a family tree — one person at the top (the **root**), and branches going down. Each person can have children, but every child has exactly ONE parent.

```
          1          ← ROOT (the top node)
         / \
        2   3        ← CHILDREN of 1
       / \   \
      4   5   6      ← LEAVES (no children)

  TERMINOLOGY:
  ─────────────────────────────────
  Root:     The topmost node (1)
  Parent:   Node above another (1 is parent of 2 and 3)
  Child:    Node below another (2 and 3 are children of 1)
  Leaf:     Node with no children (4, 5, 6)
  Edge:     Connection between parent and child
  Depth:    Distance from root (root = depth 0, node 2 = depth 1, node 4 = depth 2)
  Height:   Longest path from node to any leaf (root height = 2)
  Subtree:  A node and ALL its descendants (node 2's subtree = {2, 4, 5})
```

### Key Formulas

- A tree with **N** nodes has exactly **N - 1** edges
- A **binary tree** of height **h** has at most $2^{h+1} - 1$ nodes
- A **complete binary tree** with **N** nodes has height $\lfloor \log_2 N \rfloor$

---

## 1.2 Binary Tree — Java Implementation

A **binary tree** = each node has at most 2 children (left and right).

```java
public class TreeNode {
    int val;
    TreeNode left;
    TreeNode right;

    TreeNode(int val) {
        this.val = val;
        this.left = null;
        this.right = null;
    }
}

// Build the tree from the visual above:
//       1
//      / \
//     2   3
//    / \   \
//   4   5   6

TreeNode root = new TreeNode(1);
root.left = new TreeNode(2);
root.right = new TreeNode(3);
root.left.left = new TreeNode(4);
root.left.right = new TreeNode(5);
root.right.right = new TreeNode(6);
```

---

## 1.3 Types of Binary Trees

```
  FULL BINARY TREE:                COMPLETE BINARY TREE:
  Every node has 0 or 2 children.  All levels full except possibly last.
                                    Last level filled left to right.
       1                                1
      / \                              / \
     2   3                            2   3
    / \ / \                          / \ /
   4  5 6  7                        4  5 6

  PERFECT BINARY TREE:             BALANCED BINARY TREE:
  All levels completely full.       Height of left and right subtrees
  2^(h+1) - 1 nodes total.        differ by at most 1.
       1
      / \                               3
     2   3                             / \
    / \ / \                           2   5
   4  5 6  7                         /   / \
  (15 nodes if h=3)                 1   4   6

  DEGENERATE (SKEWED) TREE:        This is basically a linked list!
  1                                 Every operation becomes O(n)
   \                                instead of O(log n).
    2                               This is WHY balanced trees matter.
     \
      3
       \
        4
```

---

# PART 2: BINARY SEARCH TREES (BST)

---

## 2.1 What Is a BST?

A BST is a binary tree with ONE rule: **for every node, all values in the left subtree are SMALLER, and all values in the right subtree are LARGER.**

```
         8            ← root
        / \
       3   10         ← 3 < 8, 10 > 8  ✓
      / \    \
     1   6    14      ← 1 < 3, 6 > 3  ✓  |  14 > 10  ✓
        / \   /
       4   7 13       ← 4 < 6, 7 > 6  ✓  |  13 < 14  ✓

  To FIND a value (e.g., find 7):
  Start at 8 → 7 < 8, go LEFT
  At 3      → 7 > 3, go RIGHT
  At 6      → 7 > 6, go RIGHT
  At 7      → FOUND! ✓

  Only visited 4 nodes out of 9. That's O(log n) — like binary search!
```

### BST Operations — Time Complexity

| Operation | Average | Worst (skewed) |
|-----------|---------|----------------|
| Search | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Insert | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Delete | O(log n) | O(n) |
| Find Min/Max | O(log n) | O(n) |

---

## 2.2 BST Operations in Java

```java
// SEARCH in BST
public TreeNode search(TreeNode root, int target) {
    if (root == null || root.val == target) return root;
    if (target < root.val) return search(root.left, target);   // go left
    else                   return search(root.right, target);  // go right
}

// INSERT into BST
public TreeNode insert(TreeNode root, int val) {
    if (root == null) return new TreeNode(val);
    if (val < root.val)      root.left = insert(root.left, val);
    else if (val > root.val) root.right = insert(root.right, val);
    return root;  // duplicates ignored
}

// FIND MINIMUM (leftmost node)
public int findMin(TreeNode root) {
    while (root.left != null) root = root.left;
    return root.val;
}

// VALIDATE BST — is this a valid BST?
// Google LOVES this question!
public boolean isValidBST(TreeNode root) {
    return validate(root, Long.MIN_VALUE, Long.MAX_VALUE);
}

private boolean validate(TreeNode node, long min, long max) {
    if (node == null) return true;
    if (node.val <= min || node.val >= max) return false;
    return validate(node.left, min, node.val) &&
           validate(node.right, node.val, max);
}
```

---

# PART 3: TREE TRAVERSALS

The 4 ways to visit every node in a tree. **You MUST know all 4 by heart.**

---

## 3.1 Visual Overview

```
         1
        / \
       2   3
      / \
     4   5

  INORDER   (Left, Root, Right):   4, 2, 5, 1, 3
  PREORDER  (Root, Left, Right):   1, 2, 4, 5, 3
  POSTORDER (Left, Right, Root):   4, 5, 2, 3, 1
  LEVEL-ORDER (BFS, level by level): 1, 2, 3, 4, 5

  MEMORY TRICK:
  The name tells you where the ROOT goes:
  - IN-order:   Root is IN the middle     (Left, ROOT, Right)
  - PRE-order:  Root comes FIRST (PRE)    (ROOT, Left, Right)
  - POST-order: Root comes LAST (POST)    (Left, Right, ROOT)

  KEY FACT: Inorder traversal of a BST gives sorted order!
  BST:    5          Inorder: 2, 3, 5, 7, 8  ← SORTED!
         / \
        3   7
       /     \
      2       8
```

---

## 3.2 All 4 Traversals in Java

```java
// ─── INORDER (Left, Root, Right) ───
// Recursive
public void inorder(TreeNode root, List<Integer> result) {
    if (root == null) return;
    inorder(root.left, result);     // Left
    result.add(root.val);           // Root
    inorder(root.right, result);    // Right
}

// Iterative (using stack) — Google often asks for iterative versions!
public List<Integer> inorderIterative(TreeNode root) {
    List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
    Deque<TreeNode> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
    TreeNode curr = root;

    while (curr != null || !stack.isEmpty()) {
        while (curr != null) {       // Go as far left as possible
            stack.push(curr);
            curr = curr.left;
        }
        curr = stack.pop();          // Process node
        result.add(curr.val);
        curr = curr.right;           // Move to right subtree
    }
    return result;
}

// ─── PREORDER (Root, Left, Right) ───
public void preorder(TreeNode root, List<Integer> result) {
    if (root == null) return;
    result.add(root.val);           // Root
    preorder(root.left, result);    // Left
    preorder(root.right, result);   // Right
}

// ─── POSTORDER (Left, Right, Root) ───
public void postorder(TreeNode root, List<Integer> result) {
    if (root == null) return;
    postorder(root.left, result);   // Left
    postorder(root.right, result);  // Right
    result.add(root.val);           // Root
}

// ─── LEVEL-ORDER (BFS) ───
public List<List<Integer>> levelOrder(TreeNode root) {
    List<List<Integer>> result = new ArrayList<>();
    if (root == null) return result;

    Queue<TreeNode> queue = new LinkedList<>();
    queue.offer(root);

    while (!queue.isEmpty()) {
        int levelSize = queue.size();          // How many nodes at this level
        List<Integer> level = new ArrayList<>();

        for (int i = 0; i < levelSize; i++) {
            TreeNode node = queue.poll();
            level.add(node.val);
            if (node.left != null)  queue.offer(node.left);
            if (node.right != null) queue.offer(node.right);
        }
        result.add(level);
    }
    return result;
    // Returns: [[1], [2, 3], [4, 5]]
}
```

